vfs=[('/etc', True), ('/etc/default', True), ('/etc/default/useradd', b'HOME=/home'), ('/etc/groupadd.defs', b'GID_MIN=1000\nGID_MAX=6000\nMAX_MEMBERS_PER_GROUP=0'), ('/etc/login.defs', b'SYS_GID_MIN=101\nSYS_GID_MAX=100\nSYS_UID_MIN=101\nSYS_UID_MAX=100\nUID_MIN=1000\nUID_MAX=60000\nCREATE_HOME=TRUE'), ('/etc/skel', True), ('/tmp', True), ('/usr', True), ('/usr/share', True), ('/usr/share/man', True), ('/usr/share/man/alias.man', b"NAME\n\talias\nSYNOPSIS\n\talias [OPTION] [name[=value]]\nABOUT\n\tDefine or display aliases\nDESCRIPTION\n\tWithout arguments, 'alias' prints the list of aliases in the reusable form 'alias NAME=VALUE' on standard output.\n\tOtherwise, an alias is defined for each NAME whose VALUE is given. A trailing space in VALUE causes the next word to be checked for alias substitution when the alias is expanded.\n\t-p\n\t\tprint all defined aliases in a reusable format"), ('/usr/share/man/cat.man', b'NAME\n\tcat\nSYNOPSIS\n\tcat [OPTION]... [FILE]...\nABOUT\n\tconcatenate files and print on the standard output\nDESCRIPTION\n\tConcatenate FILE(s) to standard output.\n\tWith no FILE, or when FILE is -, read standard input.\n\t-n, --number\n\t\tnumber all output lines\n\t-e, --show-ends\n\t\tdisplay $ at end of each line\n\t-t, --show-tabs\n\t\tdisplay TAB characters as ^I\n\t-s, --squeeze-blank\n\t\tsuppress repeated empty output lines'), ('/usr/share/man/cd.man', b'NAME\n\tcd\nSYNOPSIS\n\tcd [dir]\nABOUT\n\tchange the shell working directory\nDESCRIPTION\n\tChange the shell working directory.\n\tChange the current directory to DIR. The default DIR is the value of the HOME shell variable.'), ('/usr/share/man/clear.man', b'NAME\n\tclear\nSYNOPSIS\n\tclear\nABOUT\n\tclear the terminal screen\nDESCRIPTION\n\tClears your screen if this is possible, including its scrollback buffer.\n\tWrites to the standard output.'), ('/usr/share/man/cp.man', b'NAME\n\tcp\nSYNOPSIS\n\tcp [OPTION]... SOURCE DEST\n\tcp [OPTION]... SOURCE... DIRECTORY\n\tcp [OPTION]... DIRECTORY SOURCE...\nABOUT\n\tcopy files and directories\nDESCRIPTION\n\tCopy SOURCE to DEST, or multiple SOURCE(s) to DIRECTORY.\n\tMandatory arguments to long options are mandatory for short options too.\n\t-R, -r, --recursive\n\t\tcopy directories recursively\n\t-v, -verbose\n\t\texplain what is being done'), ('/usr/share/man/echo.man', b'NAME\n\techo\nSYNOPSIS\n\techo [OPTION]... [STRING]...\nABOUT\n\tdisplay a line of text\nDESCRIPTION\n\tEcho the STRING(s) to standard output.\n\t-n\n\t\tdo not output the trailing newline\n\t-e\n\t\tenable interpretation of backslash escapes\n\t-E\n\t\tdisable interpretation of backslash escapes (default)'), ('/usr/share/man/ed.man', b"NAME\n\ted\nSYNOPSIS\n\ted [OPTION]... [FILE]\nABOUT\n\tline-oriented text editor\nDESCRIPTION\n\tThe ed program is a line-oriented text editor. It is used to create, display, modify and otherwise manipulate text files. Ed in restricted mode can only edit files in the current directory. Ed is the 'standard' text editor in the sense that it is the original editor for Unix, and thus widely available.\n\t-p, --prompt[=STRING]\n\t\tuse STRING as an interactive prompt\n\t-r, --restricted\n\t\trun in restricted mode\n\t-v, --verbose\n\t\tbe verbose; equivalent to the 'H' command"), ('/usr/share/man/exit.man', b'NAME\n\texit\nSYNOPSIS\n\texit\nABOUT\n\tcause normal process termination\nDESCRIPTION\n\tThe exit() function causes normal process termination.'), ('/usr/share/man/grep.man', b'NAME\n\tgrep\nSYNOPSIS\n\tgrep [OPTION]... PATTERNS\nABOUT\n\tprint lines that match patterns\nDESCRIPTION\n\tgrep searches for PATTERNS in the piped input. PATTERNS provided to grep will be returned with each line that matches a pattern.\n\t-c, --count\n\t\tSuppress normal output; instead print a count of matching lines for each input file.\n\t-i, --ignore-case\n\t\tIgnore case distinctions, so that characters that differ only in case match each other.\n\t-m NUM, --max-count NUM\n\t\tStop reading a file after NUM matching lines. When the -c or --count option is also used, grep does not output a count greater than NUM.\n\t-q, --quiet, --silent\n\t\tQuiet; do not write anything to standard output. Exit immediately with zero status if any match is found, even if an error was detected.\n\t-v, --invert-match\n\t\tInvert the sense of matching, to select non-matching lines.'), ('/usr/share/man/groupadd.man', b"NAME\n\tgroupadd\nSYNOPSIS\n\tgroupadd [OPTION] LOGIN\nABOUT\n\tcreate a new group\nDESCRIPTION\n\tThe groupadd command creates a new group account using the values specified on the command line plus the default values from the system. The new group will be entered into the system files as needed.\n\t-g, --gid\n\t\tThe numerical value of the group's ID. This value must be unique, unless the -o option is used. The value must be non-negative. The default is to use the smallest ID value greater than or equal to GID_MIN and greater than every other group.\n\t\tSee also the -r option and the GID_MAX description.\n\t-o, --non-unique\n\t\tThis option permits to add a group with a non-unique GID.\n\t-K, --key\n\t\tOverrides /etc/login.defs defaults (GID_MIN, GID_MAX and others).\n\t-r, --system\n\t\tCreate a system group.\n\t\tThe numeric identifiers of new system groups are chosen in the SYS_GID_MIN-SYS_GID_MAX range, defined in login.defs, instead of GID_MIN-GID_MAX."), ('/usr/share/man/head.man', b"NAME\n\thead\nSYNOPSIS\n\thead [OPTION]... [FILE]...\nABOUT\n\toutput the first part of files\nDESCRIPTION\n\tPrint the first 10 lines of each FILE to standard output. With more than one FILE, precede each with a header giving the file name.\n\tWith no FILE, or when FILE is -, read standard input.\n\tMandatory arguments to long options are mandatory for short options too.\n\t-n, --lines\n\t\tprint the first NUM lines instead of the first 10; with the leading '-', print all but the last NUM lines of each file"), ('/usr/share/man/help.man', b'NAME\n\thelp\nSYNOPSIS\n\thelp\nABOUT\n\tGives information about the shell and commands\nDESCRIPTION\n\tOutputs information about the shell and commands along with what they do.'), ('/usr/share/man/hostname.man', b"NAME\n\thostname\nSYNOPSIS\n\thostname\nABOUT\n\tshow the system's host name\nDESCRIPTION\n\tHostname is used to display the system's DNS name."), ('/usr/share/man/id.man', b'NAME\n\tid\nSYNOPSIS\n\tid [OPTION] [USER]\nABOUT\n\tprint real and effective user and group IDs\nDESCRIPTION\n\tPrint user and group information for the specified USER, or (when USER omitted) for the current user.\n\t-g, --group\n\t\tprint only the effective group ID\n\t-G, --groups\n\t\tprint all group IDs\n\t-u, --user\n\t\tprint only the effective user ID'), ('/usr/share/man/link.man', b'NAME\n\tlink\nSYNOPSIS\n\tlink FILE1 FILE2\nABOUT\n\tcall the link function to create a link to a file\nDESCRIPTION\n\tCall the link function to create a link named FILE2 to an existing FILE1.'), ('/usr/share/man/login.man', b"NAME\n\tlogin\nSYNOPSIS\n\tlogin [OPTION] username\nABOUT\n\tbegin session on the system\nDESCRIPTION\n\tThe login program is used to establish a new session with the system. It is normally invoked automatically by responding to the login: prompt on the user's terminal.\n\tThe user is then prompted for a password, where appropriate. Echoing is disabled to prevent revealing the password. Only a small number of password failures are permitted before login exits and the communications link is severed.\n\tYour user and group ID will be set according to their values in the /etc/passwd file. The value for $USER, $LOGNAME are set according to the appropriate fields in the password entry.\n\t-f\n\t\tDo not perform authentication, user is preauthenticated.\n\t\tNote: In that case, username is mandatory.\n\t-p\n\t\tPreserve environment."), ('/usr/share/man/logout.man', b"NAME\n\tlogout\nSYNOPSIS\n\tlogout\nABOUT\n\texits a session on the system\nDESCRIPTION\n\tWhen you terminate a login shell (via the commands 'exit', 'logout'), you are logged out completely"), ('/usr/share/man/ls.man', b"NAME\n\tls\nSYNOPSIS\n\tls [OPTION]\nABOUT\n\tlist directory contents\nDESCRIPTION\n\tList information about the files.\n\t-a, --all\n\t\tdo not ignore entries starting with\n\t-A, --almost-all\n\t\tdo not list implied . and ..\n\t--color[=WHEN]\n    \tcolorize the output; WHEN can be 'always' (default if omitted), 'auto', or 'never'\n\t-r, --reverse\n\t\treverse order while sorting\n\t-p\n\t\tappend / indicator to directories\n\t-m\n\t\tfill width with a comma separated list of entries\n\t-q, --quote-name\n \t\tenclose entry names in double quotes\n\t-n, --literal\n\t\tprint entry names without quoting"), ('/usr/share/man/man.man', b"NAME\n\tman\nSYNOPSIS\n\tman [whatis options] page...\nABOUT\n\tan interface to the on-line reference manuals\nDESCRIPTION\n\tThe man command is used as the system's manual pager. Each page argument given to man is normally the name of a program, utility or function. The manual page associated with each of these arguments is then found and displayed.\n\t-f, --what-is\n\t\tDisplay a short description from the manual page, if available."), ('/usr/share/man/mkdir.man', b'NAME\n\tmkdir\nSYNOPSIS\n\tmkdir [OPTION]... DIRECTORY...\nABOUT\n\tmake directories\nDESCRIPTION\n\tCreate the DIRECTORY(ies), if they do not already exist.\n\tMandatory arguments to long options are mandatory for short options too.\n\t-p, --parents\n\t\tno error if existing, make parent directories as needed\n\t-v, --verbose\n\t\tprint a message for each created directory'), ('/usr/share/man/mv.man', b'NAME\n\tmv\nSYNOPSIS\n\tmv [OPTION]... SOURCE DEST\n\tmv [OPTION]... SOURCE... DIRECTORY\n\tmv [OPTION]... DIRECTORY SOURCE...\nABOUT\n\tmove (rename) files\nDESCRIPTION\n\tRename SOURCE to DEST, or move SOURCE(s) to DIRECTORY.\n\tMandatory arguments to long options are mandatory for short options too.\n\t-v, -verbose\n\t\texplain what is being done'), ('/usr/share/man/passwd.man', b'NAME\n\tpasswd\nSYNOPSIS\n\tpasswd [LOGIN]\nABOUT\n\tchange user password\nDESCRIPTION\n\tThe passwd command changes passwords for the current user account, or the one provided by LOGIN.'), ('/usr/share/man/ping.man', b'NAME\n\tping\nSYNOPSIS\n\tping [OPTION]... {DESTINATION}\nABOUT\n\tsend ICMP ECHO_REQUEST to network hosts\nDESCRIPTION\n\tping uses the ICMP protocol\'s mandatory ECHO_REQUEST datagram to elicit an ICMP ECHO_RESPONSE from a host or gateway. ECHO_REQUEST datagrams ("pings") have an IP and ICMP header, followed by a struct timeval and then an arbitrary number of "pad" bytes used to fill out the packet.\n\t-c\n\t\tStop after sending count ECHO_REQUEST packets. With deadline option, ping waits for count ECHO_REPLY packets, until the timeout expires.\n\t-f\n\t\tFlood ping. If interval is not given, it sets interval to zero and outputs packets as fast as they come back or one hundred times per second, whichever is more. Also set output to quiet.\n\t-i\n\t\tWait interval seconds between sending each packet. The default is to wait for one second between each packet normally, or not to wait in flood mode. Only super-user may set interval to values less 0.2 seconds.\n\t-q\n\t\tQuiet output. Nothing is displayed except the summary lines at startup time and when finished.\n\t-s\n\t\tSpecifies the number of data bytes to be sent. The default is 56, which translates into 64 ICMP data bytes when combined with the 8 bytes of ICMP header data.\n\t-w\n\t\tSpecify a timeout, in seconds, before ping exits regardless of how many packets have been sent or received. In this case ping does not stop after count packet are sent, it waits either for deadline expire or until count probes are answered.\n\t-W\n\t\tTime to wait for a response, in seconds.'), ('/usr/share/man/pwd.man', b'NAME\n\tpwd\nSYNOPSIS\n\tpwd\nABOUT\n\tprint name of current/working directory\nDESCRIPTION\n\tList information about the files.'), ('/usr/share/man/rm.man', b'NAME\n\trm\nSYNOPSIS\n\trm [OPTION]... [FILE]...\nABOUT\n\tremove files or directories\nDESCRIPTION\n\tIf the -I option is given, and there are more than three files or the -r, -R, or --recursive are given, then rm prompts the user for whether to proceed with the entire operation. If the response is not affirmative, the entire command is aborted.\n\tOtherwise, if a file is unwritable, standard input is a terminal, and the -f or --force option is not given, or the -i  option is given, rm prompts the user for whether to remove the file. If the response is not affirmative, the file is skipped.\n\t-f, --force\n\t\tignore nonexistent files and arguments, never prompt\n\t-i\n\t\tprompt before every removal\n\t-I\n\t\tprompt once before removing more than three files, or when removing recursively; less intrusive than -i, while still giving protection against most mistakes\n\t-r, -R, --recursive\n\t\tremove directories and their contents recursively\n\t-d, --dir\n\t\tremove empty directories'), ('/usr/share/man/rmdir.man', b"NAME\n\trmdir\nSYNOPSIS\n\trmdir [OPTION]... DIRECTORY...\nABOUT\n\tremove empty directories\nDESCRIPTION\n\tRemove the DIRECTORY(ies), if they are empty.\n\t-p, --parents\n\t\tremove DIRECTORY and its ancestors; e.g., 'rmdir -p a/b/c' is similar to 'rmdir a/b/c a/b a'\n\t-v, --verbose\n\t\toutput a diagnostic for every directory processed"), ('/usr/share/man/shutdown.man', b'NAME\n\tshutdown\nSYNOPSIS\n\tshutdown [OPTION]\nABOUT\n\tpower-off the machine\nDESCRIPTION\n\tShutdown may be used to power-off or reset the machine.\n\t--reset\n\t\tUse to reset and remove all content from the machine. Must be used in conjunction with --confirm to initiate system reset.\n\t--confirm\n\t\tUsed to verify the presence of --reset when required. '), ('/usr/share/man/sort.man', b'NAME\n\tsort\nSYNOPSIS\n\tsort [OPTION]...\nABOUT\n\tsort lines of text files\nDESCRIPTION\n\tWrite sorted concatenation of lines from piped input.\n\tWith no options, matching lines are merged to the first occurrence.\n\tMandatory arguments to long options are mandatory for short options too.\n\t-i, --ignore-case\n\t\tfold lower case to upper case characters\n\t-r, --reverse\n\t\treverse the result of comparisons'), ('/usr/share/man/tail.man', b"NAME\n\ttail\nSYNOPSIS\n\ttail [OPTION]... [FILE]...\nABOUT\n\toutput the last part of files\nDESCRIPTION\n\tPrint the last 10 lines of each FILE to standard output. With more than one FILE, precede each with a header giving the file name.\n\tWith no FILE, or when FILE is -, read standard input.\n\tMandatory arguments to long options are mandatory for short options too.\n\t-n, --lines\n\t\tprint the last NUM lines instead of the last 10; with the leading '-', print all but the last NUM lines of each file"), ('/usr/share/man/touch.man', b'NAME\n\ttouch\nSYNOPSIS\n\ttouch [FILE]...\nABOUT\n\tchange file timestamps\nDESCRIPTION\n\tUpdate the access and modification times of each FILE to the current time.\n\tA FILE argument that does not exist is created empty.'), ('/usr/share/man/unalias.man', b'NAME\n\tunalias\nSYNOPSIS\n\tunalias [OPTION] [names]\nABOUT\n\tRemove aliases\nDESCRIPTION\n\tRemove each NAME from the list of defined aliases.\n\t-a\n\t\tremove all alias definitions'), ('/usr/share/man/uname.man', b'NAME\n\tuname\nSYNOPSIS\n\tuname\nABOUT\n\tprint system information\nDESCRIPTION\n\tPrint certain system information.\n\t-a, --all\n\t\tprint  all  information\n\t-n, --nodename\n\t\tprint the network node hostname\n\t-r, --kernel-release\n\t\tprint the kernel release\n\t-s, --kernel-name\n\t\tprint the kernel name\n\t-v, --kernel-version\n\t\tprint the kernel version\n'), ('/usr/share/man/uniq.man', b'NAME\n\tuniq\nSYNOPSIS\n\tuniq [OPTION]...\nABOUT\n\treport or omit repeated lines\nDESCRIPTION\n\tFilter adjacent matching lines from piped input.\n\tWith no options, matching lines are merged to the first occurrence.\n\tMandatory arguments to long options are mandatory for short options too.\n\t-c, --count\n\t\tprefix lines by the number of occurrences\n\t-d, --repeated\n\t\tonly print duplicate lines, one for each group\n\t-i, --ignore-case\n\t\tignore differences in case when comparing\n\t-u, --unique\n\t\tonly print unique lines'), ('/usr/share/man/unlink.man', b'NAME\n\tunlink\nSYNOPSIS\n\tlink FILE\nABOUT\n\tcall the unlink function to remove the specified file\nDESCRIPTION\n\tCall the unlink function to remove the specified FILE.'), ('/usr/share/man/useradd.man', b"NAME\n\tuseradd\nSYNOPSIS\n\tuseradd [OPTION] LOGIN\nABOUT\n\tcreate a new user or update default new user information\nDESCRIPTION\n\tuseradd is a low level utility for adding users.\n\t-c, --comment\n\t\tAny text string. It is generally a short description of the login, and is currently used as the field for the user's full name.\n\t-g, --gid\n\t\tThe group name id of the user's initial login group. A group number must refer to an already existing group.\n\t-G, --groups\n\t\tA list of supplementary groups which the user is also a member of. Each group is separated from the next by a comma, with no intervening whitespace. The groups are subject to the same restrictions as the group given with the -g option. The default is for the user to belong only to the initial group.\n\t-K, --key\n\t\tOverrides /etc/login.defs defaults (UID_MIN, UID_MAX, and others).\n\t-m, --create-home\n\t\tCreate the user's home directory if it does not exist. The files and directories contained in the skeleton directory will be copied to the home directory.\n\t-o, --non-unique\n\t\tAllow the creation of a user account with a duplicate (non-unique) UID.\n\t\tThis option is only valid in combination with the -u option.\n\t-p, --password\n\t\tThe encrypted password. The default is to disable the password.\n\t\tNote: This option is not recommended because the password (or encrypted password) will be visible by users listing the processes.\n\t\tYou should make sure the password respects the system's password policy.\n\t-r, --system\n\t\tCreate a system account.\n\t\tSystem users will be created with no aging information in /etc/shadow, and their numeric identifiers are chosen in the SYS_UID_MIN-SYS_UID_MAX range, defined in /etc/login.defs, instead of UID_MIN-UID_MAX (and their GID counterparts for the creation of groups).\n\t-u, --uid\n\t\tThe numerical value of the user's ID. This value must be unique, unless the -o option is used. The value must be non-negative. The default is to use the smallest ID value greater than or equal to UID_MIN and greater than every other user."), ('/usr/share/man/wget.man', b'NAME\n\twget\nSYNOPSIS\n\twget [OPTION]... [URL]...\nABOUT\n\tThe non-interactive network downloader\nDESCRIPTION\n\tA utility for non-interactive download of files from the Web. It supports HTTP, HTTPS, and FTP protocols,\n\t-v, --verbose\n\t\tTurn on verbose output, with all the available data. The default output is verbose.\n\t-nv, --no-verbose\n\t\tTurn off verbose without being completely quiet (use -q for that), which means that error messages and basic information still get printed.\n\t-i, --input-file\n\t\tRead URLs from a local file.\n\t\tIf this function is used, no URLs need be present on the command line. If there are URLs both on the command line and in an input file, those on the command lines will be the first ones to be retrieved.\n\t-t, --tries\n\t\tSet number of tries to number. The default is to retry 20 times.'), ('/usr/share/man/whoami.man', b'NAME\n\twhoami\nSYNOPSIS\n\twhoami\nABOUT\n\tprint effective userid\nDESCRIPTION\n\tPrint the user name associated with the current effective user ID.')]